sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K602004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: D. radiodurans PprI with LacI constitutive promoter and ribosome binding site attached upstream. Constitutively expresses PprI. Should increase DNA damage repair capability and radioresistance of host E. coli.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Shao Thing TEOH

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K118022
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: cex coding sequence encoding Cellulomonas fimi exoglucanase
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The fungus ''Cellulomonas fimi'' uses an exoglucanase (from ''cex'') along with 3 endoglucanases in the degradation of cellulose into cellobiose, before use B-glucosidase to catalyse the conversion of cellobiose to D-glucose.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Andrew Hall
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The original sequence had a PstI site for 781-786. We added the silent mutation CAG->CAA (Gln) by MABEL to remove this site.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K602000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional regulator involved in the expression of many DNA damage response proteins in Deinococcus radiodurans.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Toshiyuki Otake, Youfeng Lin, Shuhei Yasumoto, Takahiro Saka, Rie Takino, Shaothing Teoh
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Obtained by PCR from genomic DNA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We have designed part according to BBF RFC 54, which modifies the prefix and suffix to allow for the use of shorter PCR cloning primers but can be assembled in the usual way (i.e. Standard Assembly, RFC 10).
